But for example, on both sides, some of the momentum portfolios, I really think momentum, because of the nature of turnover required, you really want more frequent rebalance, but constrain the rebalance to get to the momentum factor a little bit more. On the good side is that I'm actually, I worked at the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago for a year as a social economist in 1999 to 2000, which is really interesting time for macroeconomics. Of course, for me, it was my first job coming to US and graduate. I always remember those days. At that time, I was passionate to be a macroeconomist, actually. But for a long while, I was also skeptical. I actually, the Chicago Activity Index, I was one of the researchers who worked on that and Stock Watson's inflation forecasting paper. You know, use 80 different macro series. So I worked on a lot of macro data. Yet, for a long time, I was very skeptical of how much macro information can be used in factor research. But I think probably in the last couple years, I have started to think a little bit more in this area. And some of the implementation of taking into account of the macro information into portfolios could potentially, I'm not an expert, but I'm not an expert, but I'm not an expert on macro data. I'm not 100% convinced yet, but that really made me pay attention to it. So I think kind of doing my own research and also looking at how others have done it and really going back to the early years when I was just purely looking at macro forecasting, like inflation forecasting. So that's an area which I think other, there are some innovative strategies.
